	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Is thus your first time programming anything?  Assembly? Or just the Nes?<br /><br />Like these guys i can't imagine how a programming on the nes video would be helpful.  The only exception would maybe be a quick video showing how to compile and get the needed programs set up.<br /><br />If you really want a video i would suggest looking at any programming videos, our specifically assembly of any type.  If you know assembly for any CPU you can figure out to program the nes easily with the supporting docs.  Like they are saying, when you have questions of specific instructions and such you want a doc to search and read  NOT a video.<br /><br />Aside from that there is only one way to learn assembly and most programming, actually do it and practice with increasing complexity.<br /><br />Edit:  if you do understand assembly and CPU basics one video that helped me described the 6502 architecture.  In my opinion the key to being good with assembly is fully understanding the hardware/architecture.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
